# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sanic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sanic/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] The **Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface** (**ASGI**) is a calling convention for web servers to forward requests to asynchronous-capable Python frameworks, and applications.
[src:sanic/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] It is built as a successor to the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI).
[src:sanic/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] Where WSGI provided a standard for synchronous Python applications, ASGI provides one for both asynchronous and synchronous applications, with a WSGI backwards-compatibility implementation and multiple servers and application frameworks.
[src:sanic/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] ASGI is also designed to be a superset of WSGI, and there's a defined way of translating between the two, allowing WSGI applications to be run inside ASGI servers through a translation wrapper (provided in the asgiref library).
[src:sanic/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] A threadpool can be used to run the synchronous WSGI applications away from the async event loop.
[src:sanic/getting-started] Before we begin, make sure you are running Python 3.9 or higher.
[src:sanic/getting-started] Currently, Sanic is works with Python versions 3.9 – 3.13.
[src:sanic/getting-started] If you have ever used one of the many decorator based frameworks, this probably looks somewhat familiar to you.
[src:sanic/getting-started] If you are coming from Flask or another framework, there are a few important things to point out.
[src:sanic/getting-started] Remember, Sanic aims for performance, flexibility, and ease of use.
[src:sanic/getting-started] These guiding principles have tangible impact on the API and how it works.
[src:sanic/getting-started] Let's save the above file as `server.py`.
[src:sanic/getting-started] Other frameworks come with a built in development server and explicitly say that it is *only* intended for development use.
[src:sanic/getting-started] Sanic intentionally aims for a clean and unopinionated feature list.
[src:sanic/getting-started] The project does not want to require you to build your application in a certain way, and tries to avoid prescribing specific development patterns.
[src:sanic/getting-started] There are a number of third-party plugins that are built and maintained by the community to add additional features that do not otherwise meet the requirements of the core repository.
[src:sanic/getting-started] The preferred method to set it up is to install it along with Sanic, but you can also install the packages on their own.
[src:sanic/getting-started] Starting in v21.12, Sanic will automatically setup Sanic Extensions if it is in the same environment.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:sanic/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic made a cameo in the arcade game *Rad Mobile* (1990) before starring in *Sonic the Hedgehog*, a platform game for the Sega Genesis, in 1991.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sega sought a mascot to compete with Nintendo's Mario, and Ohshima designed Sonic based on a prototype programmed by Naka.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic's design was influenced by a variety of sources, including Felix the Cat, Mickey Mouse, Michael Jackson, and Santa Claus; his pigmentation was chosen to match Sega's cobalt blue logo.
[src:sanic/sanic] Yuji Uekawa redesigned Sonic for *Sonic Adventure* (1998) to suit the franchise's transition to 3D computer graphics, with a more mature look designed to appeal to older players.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic is one of the most famous video game characters and an established pop culture icon.
[src:sanic/sanic] Journalists regard him as one of the greatest video game characters and his popularity inspired many imitators.
[src:sanic/sanic] His likeness has been featured in merchandise and Sega sponsorships.
[src:sanic/sanic] The *Sonic* series is one of the bestselling game franchises and was key to Sega's success during the 16-bit era in the 1990s.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic has been adapted in comics, animations, and films, including a live-action film franchise distributed by Paramount Pictures in which he is voiced by Ben Schwartz.
[src:sanic/sanic] While Sega was seeking a flagship series to compete with Nintendo's Mario series, several character designs were submitted by its research and development department.
[src:sanic/sanic] Naoto Ohshima took some of these internal designs with him on a trip to New York City and sought feedback by asking random passersby at Central Park their opinions; of the designs, the spiky teal hedgehog, initially codenamed "Mr.
[src:sanic/sanic] Harinezumi*), led this informal poll, followed by Eggman and the dog character.
[src:sanic/sanic] Ohshima felt that people selected it because it "transcends race and gender and things like that".
[src:sanic/sanic] On return to Japan, Ohshima pitched this to the department, and the hedgehog was ultimately selected as the new mascot.
[src:sanic/sanic] The detailed design of Sonic was aimed to be something that could be easily drawn by children and be familiar, as well as exhibit a "cool" attitude, representative of the United States at the time.
[src:sanic/sanic] To help sell the idea to Sega's higher-ups, Ohshima pitched the concept framed by a fictional fighter pilot that had earned the name "Hedgehog" due to his spiky hair, and had decorated his plane with images of Sonic.
[src:sanic/sanic] When this pilot retired, he married a children's book author, who wrote stories about the Sonic character, the first which became the plot for the first *Sonic* game; Ohshima stated that this influence can be seen in the logo of the game, which features Sonic in a pilot's wing emblem.
[src:sanic/sanic] The origins of *Sonic* can be traced farther back to a draft created by Naoto Ōshima in 1989, which years later turned into Sonic.
[src:sanic/sanic] Yuji Naka implemented the idea of a character running inside loops with an algorithm that allowed a sprite to move smoothly on a curve by determining its position with a dot matrix.
[src:sanic/sanic] This concept was subsequently fleshed out by designer Hirokazu Yasuhara.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic was created without the ability to swim because of a mistaken assumption by Yuji Naka that all hedgehogs could not do so.
[src:sanic/sanic] A group of fifteen people started working on the first *Sonic the Hedgehog* game, and renamed themselves Sonic Team.
[src:sanic/sanic] The game's soundtrack was composed by Masato Nakamura of the band Dreams Come True.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sega sponsored the group's "Wonder 3" tour, painting Sonic on the tour bus, distributing pamphlets advertising the game, and having footage of the game broadcast above stage prior to its release.
[src:sanic/sanic] The original concepts gave Sonic fangs and put him in a band with a human girlfriend named Madonna.
[src:sanic/sanic] However, a team from Sega of America, led by Madeline Schroeder, who calls herself "Sonic's mother", "softened" the character up for an American audience by removing those elements.
[src:sanic/sanic] This sparked a heated issue with Sonic Team.
[src:sanic/sanic] Naka later admitted that it was probably for the best.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic's appearance varies greatly depending on the medium and the style in which he is drawn.
[src:sanic/sanic] In the video games, Sonic's original design by Ohshima was short and round, with short quills, a round body, and no visible irises.
[src:sanic/sanic] Artwork featuring this design and drawn by Akira Watanabe was displayed on the package artwork for *Sonic the Hedgehog*.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic's proportions would change for the release of *Sonic the Hedgehog 2* on the Mega Drive; Sonic's head to height ratio was changed from 1:2 to 1:2.5.
[src:sanic/sanic] For the 1998 release of *Sonic Adventure*, Sonic was redesigned by Yuji Uekawa as a character with longer legs and a less spherical body, longer and more drooping quills, and green-colored irises.
[src:sanic/sanic] For the 2006 game, Sonic was redesigned to make him look adult-like and taller to appeal to the next generation players.
[src:sanic/sanic] This was also done because Sonic would interact with humans more often and his design was supposed to fit.
[src:sanic/sanic] An alternative "Werehog" form was introduced in *Sonic Unleashed*, placing more emphasis on Sonic's melee skills rather than speed.
[src:sanic/sanic] Although Tetsu Katano acknowledged the large negative fan response to the Werehog, he believes it could return in a future game.
[src:sanic/sanic] Bob Raffei, CEO of *Sonic Boom* developer Big Red Button, stated that *Sonic Boom*'s Sonic is "very different... both in tone and art direction." That version has blue-furred arms, more quills, and wears a brown neckerchief around his neck and athletic sports tape on his wrists and shoes.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic originally had a few voice samples in *Sonic CD*, with designer Masato Nishimura providing the voice.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic's first true voice actor was Takeshi Kusao for the arcade game *SegaSonic the Hedgehog*, with Junichi Kanemaru continually voicing the role beginning with the release of *Sonic Adventure*.
[src:sanic/sanic] Kanemaru also voices Sonic in *Sonic X*, *Sonic Boom*, and the Japanese dub of the *Wreck-It Ralph* films.
[src:sanic/sanic] In *Sonic Unleashed*, Sonic was voiced by Tomokazu Seki while in Werehog form.
[src:sanic/sanic] The first English portrayal of Sonic was by Jaleel White in the DiC animated series *Adventures of Sonic the Hedgehog*, *Sonic SatAM*, and *Sonic Underground*.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sam Vincent provided his singing voice in the latter DiC cartoon.
[src:sanic/sanic] Starting with *Sonic Adventure*, Sonic was voiced in English by Ryan Drummond.
[src:sanic/sanic] Drummond was replaced by Jason Griffith starting from *Sonic X*, with Griffith voicing Sonic within the games starting with *Shadow The Hedgehog* in 2005.
[src:sanic/sanic] Griffith was replaced by Roger Craig Smith, starting with *Sonic Free Riders* and *Sonic Colors*.
[src:sanic/sanic] Smith announced on his Twitter account on January 29, 2021, that he would no longer voice Sonic, with his departure confirmed by Sega the same day.
[src:sanic/sanic] On May 26, 2021, Smith and Sega confirmed that he was voicing Sonic once again.
[src:sanic/sanic] Ben Schwartz voiced Sonic in the 2020 feature film and its 2022 and 2024 sequels.
[src:sanic/sanic] Canadian actor Deven Mack, voices Sonic in the *Sonic Prime* animated series.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic's first shown appearance in a video game was in the 1990 arcade racing game *Rad Mobile*, as a decorative ornament hanging from a rearview mirror.
[src:sanic/sanic] This was followed by an unlicensed appearance in *The Adventures of Quik & Silva* as a villain.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic's first playable appearance was in the platform game *Sonic the Hedgehog* for the Sega Mega Drive/Genesis, which also introduced his nemesis Dr.
[src:sanic/sanic] His two-tailed fox friend Tails joined him in the game's 1992 sequel, *Sonic the Hedgehog 2*.
[src:sanic/sanic] When all the Chaos Emeralds have been collected, Sonic can transform into Super Sonic by collecting 50 rings.
[src:sanic/sanic] Super Sonic is nearly invincible, runs faster, and jumps farther, but loses one ring per second and reverts to normal when his rings are depleted.
[src:sanic/sanic] *Sonic CD*, released in 1993, introduced Sonic's self-appointed girlfriend Amy Rose and recurring robotic doppelgänger Metal Sonic as Sonic traveled through time to ensure a good future for the world.
[src:sanic/sanic] *Sonic 3* and its direct sequel *Sonic & Knuckles*, both released in 1994, saw Sonic and Tails battle Robotnik again, with the additional threat of Knuckles, who is tricked by Robotnik into thinking Sonic is a threat.
[src:sanic/sanic] *Sonic 4* (2010–2012) continues where the story of *Sonic 3* left off, reducing Sonic to the only playable character and releasing in episodic installments.
[src:sanic/sanic] The second episode sees the return of both Tails as Sonic's sidekick and Metal Sonic as a recurring enemy.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic has also been featured in other games of many genres other than 2D and 3D platform games.
[src:sanic/sanic] Critics and fans have occasionally questioned why Sonic uses vehicles in several of the racing games, given his latent speed; however, it has been explained by Sega and in some official *Sonic* media that he does so in order to compete fairly with others in races.
[src:sanic/sanic] Robotnik's Mean Bean Machine* (1993), *Knuckles' Chaotix* (1995), *Tails' Skypatrol* (1995), *Tails Adventure* (1995), and *Shadow the Hedgehog* (2005) starred supporting characters of the *Sonic* series, although Sonic himself cameos in most of them.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic makes cameos in various other games, such as *Billy Hatcher and the Giant Egg* as a power-up, in the main hallway in *Phantasy Star Universe*, and in the 2008 remake of *Samba de Amigo*.
[src:sanic/sanic] He is also a playable character in *Christmas NiGHTS into Dreams*.
[src:sanic/sanic] Nintendo, Sega's former rival, references Sonic in *Donkey Kong Country 2: Diddy's Kong Quest*, by showing Sonic's shoes next to a trash can that reads "No Hopers" on the Cranky's Video Game Heroes screen.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic has appeared in several crossover games, including playable appearances in *Super Smash Bros.
[src:sanic/sanic] Brawl* (2008), *Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U* (2014), and *Super Smash Bros.
[src:sanic/sanic] He appears in the crossover party game series *Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games* and is also a playable character in all three *Sega Superstars* games.
[src:sanic/sanic] An official Sonic the Hedgehog skin is available in the platformer battle royale game *Fall Guys*.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic appears as a playable character in *Puyo Puyo Tetris 2* via free update.
[src:sanic/sanic] An official Sonic the Hedgehog world with skins are available with DLC in *Minecraft*.
[src:sanic/sanic] He is also appears as an unlockable playable character in *Super Monkey Ball: Banana Blitz HD*, *Super Monkey Ball Banana Mania* and *Super Monkey Ball Banana Rumble*.
[src:sanic/sanic] The first three animated series featuring Sonic were created by the international company DiC.
[src:sanic/sanic] The first of these series, *Adventures of Sonic the Hedgehog*, premiered in 1993, and depicts Sonic and his friend Tails opposing Doctor Ivo Robotnik and his robots on the planet Mobius.
[src:sanic/sanic] Another animated series premiering the same year, simply titled *Sonic the Hedgehog*, depicts Sonic and a group of rebels aiming to defeat Robotnik in a futuristic version of Mobius.
[src:sanic/sanic] The third animated series, *Sonic Underground*, premiered in 1999, and features Sonic as the protagonist alongside his siblings Sonia and Manic.
[src:sanic/sanic] In 1996, a two-part OVA, *Sonic the Hedgehog,* was released in Japan.
[src:sanic/sanic] For the American release, the two episodes combined and released as *Sonic the Hedgehog: The Movie* by ADV Films.
[src:sanic/sanic] A new series, *Sonic X,* began airing in 2003.
[src:sanic/sanic] The 78-episode anime series detailed Sonic's struggle to protect the Chaos Emeralds from Eggman and new villains.
[src:sanic/sanic] Featuring a cross-world and interstellar journey, *Sonic X* depicted Sonic and his human friend Chris Thorndyke in quests to save the world.
[src:sanic/sanic] *Sonic: Night of the Werehog* is a short film produced by Sega's VE Animation Studio, released to coincide with the release of *Sonic Unleashed*.
[src:sanic/sanic] In the film, Sonic and Chip enter a haunted house, and must deal with two ghosts trying to scare them in attempt to win the heart of the girl ghost.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic also makes multiple cameo appearances in the Disney film *Wreck-It Ralph* (2012) and its sequel *Ralph Breaks the Internet* (2018).
[src:sanic/sanic] In October 2013, Sega announced a CGI animated series, *Sonic Boom*.
[src:sanic/sanic] The show ran for 104 11-minute episodes between 2014 and 2017 on Cartoon Network in the U.S. and the UK, and Canal J and Gulli in France.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic makes several appearances in 2014 anime *Hi-sCoool!
[src:sanic/sanic] SeHa Girls* and guest-stars in the *OK K.O.!
[src:sanic/sanic] Let's Be Heroes* episode "Let's Meet Sonic".
[src:sanic/sanic] In February 2021, *Sonic Prime* was announced by Netflix with a 2022 release window, though the series' development was initially revealed in a deleted tweet in December 2020.
[src:sanic/sanic] The show is primarily for children ages six to eleven, as well as longtime fans of the franchise.
[src:sanic/sanic] In October 2022, Netflix set its release for December.
[src:sanic/sanic] In the series, after recklessly breaking the Paradox Prism which breaks the entire universe and creates several alternative dimensions and versions of his friends, Sonic desperately seeks to restore them and embarks on a mission to find the shards of the Prism and fix it.
[src:sanic/sanic] On June 10, 2014, a film based on the *Sonic* series was announced.
[src:sanic/sanic] Simply known as *Sonic the Hedgehog*, it was produced by Neal Moritz on his Original Film banner alongside Takeshi Ito and Mie Onishi, with Toby Ascher as executive producer.
[src:sanic/sanic] The film was written by Pat Casey and Josh Miller and produced as a joint venture between Paramount Pictures and Marza Animation Planet.
[src:sanic/sanic] The film is a live-action and CGI hybrid.
[src:sanic/sanic] The movie was filmed in 2018, with a release date initially set for November 8, 2019.
[src:sanic/sanic] Upon the release of the film's first trailer in late April 2019, however, Sonic's appearance was heavily criticized, leading to the director, Jeff Fowler, to announce a redesign of him, pushing back the release date to February 14, 2020.
[src:sanic/sanic] The second trailer for the film was released on November 12, 2019, featuring the redesign, which drew in a far more positive response from both fans and critics alike.
[src:sanic/sanic] In the first film, it centers on Sonic, born with supersonic speed powers and abilities, who befriends the sheriff named Tom Wachowski, to stop the villainous Dr.
[src:sanic/sanic] Robotnik who plots to have Sonic's speed powers for world domination.
[src:sanic/sanic] Particular issues with his design included his teeth and legs.
[src:sanic/sanic] According to Paramount marketing president Marc Weinstock, the negative reaction to the original design resulted in a change to how video game adaptations are handled at the company.
[src:sanic/sanic] A sequel, *Sonic the Hedgehog 2*, was released on April 8, 2022, and it centers on Sonic and Tails on a race to prevent Robotnik and Knuckles from getting the hands on the Master Emerald.
[src:sanic/sanic] The original design of Sonic from the first movie's initial trailer appears in *Chip 'n Dale: Rescue Rangers*, voiced by Tim Robinson.
[src:sanic/sanic] Named "Ugly Sonic", he is portrayed as a washed up actor looking to make a comeback after he was kicked off the film.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic briefly appears as a player's avatar in the 2018 film *Ready Player One*.
[src:sanic/sanic] Numerous British publications, including "Sega handbook" *Stay Sonic* (1993), four novels published by Virgin Books (1993–1994) and the comic book *Sonic the Comic* (1993–2001), published by Fleetway Publications/Egmont Publishing, used this premise as their basis.
[src:sanic/sanic] The American comics published by Archie Comics, *Sonic the Hedgehog* (1993–2017), *Sonic X* (2005–2008), and *Sonic Universe* (2009–2017) are based on the settings established by earlier animated TV series, the ABC "SatAM" cartoon, the *Sonic X* anime, and an expansion to the series, respectively.
[src:sanic/sanic] The former series is currently the second longest-running licensed comic series in the history of American comic books, second only to Marvel's Conan series (first issue released in 1970).
[src:sanic/sanic] In France two comic books named "Sonic Adventures" were published by Sirène in 1994.
[src:sanic/sanic] *Guinness World Records* recognized Sonic comic as the longest-running comic based on a game.
[src:sanic/sanic] Archie Comics also released a twelve part crossover with Mega Man beginning in 2013.
[src:sanic/sanic] The Archie comics were later succeeded by a new comic series by IDW Publishing in 2018, which is currently ongoing.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic has also been featured in two different manga.
[src:sanic/sanic] One series was simply called *Sonic the Hedgehog*, and featured a story about a normal hedgehog boy named Nicky who can change into Sonic.
[src:sanic/sanic] The other series was a compilation of short stories and was separated into two volumes, the first being called *Dash and Spin*, and the other called *Super Fast Sonic!!*.
[src:sanic/sanic] In 2025, Sonic was featured in the crossover miniseries *DC X Sonic the Hedgehog*, in which he and his friends team up with the Justice League to stop Darkseid from harnessing the Chaos Emeralds and using their power to conquer the multiverse.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic partners with the Flash, and the frequently debates him over which of them is faster.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic later returns in the sequel *Metal Legion*, in which he and his friends team up to battle Doctor Eggman and the Legion of Doom.
[src:sanic/sanic] According to various official materials from Sega, Sonic is described as a character who is "like the wind": a drifter who lives as he wants, and makes life a series of events and adventures.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic hates oppression and staunchly defends freedom.
[src:sanic/sanic] Although he is mostly quick-witted and easygoing, he has a short temper and is often impatient with slower things.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic is a habitual daredevil hedgehog who is honest, loyal to friends, keeps his promises, and dislikes tears.
[src:sanic/sanic] He took the young Tails under his wing like a little brother, and is uninterested in marital proposals from Amy Rose.
[src:sanic/sanic] In times of crisis, he focuses intensely on the challenge, as if his personality had undergone an astonishing change.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic's greatest strength is his running speed, being known in the game's universe as the world's fastest hedgehog.
[src:sanic/sanic] Many of his abilities are variations on the tendency for hedgehogs to roll into tight balls for protection with the addition of spinning his body.
[src:sanic/sanic] Since his introduction in 1991's *Sonic the Hedgehog*, Sonic's primary offensive maneuver is the basic "Spin Attack" (or "Sonic Spin Attack").
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic's only weakness is that he cannot swim, sinking like a rock if plunged to a deep body of water.
[src:sanic/sanic] The reason for this is because Yuji Naka had a misunderstanding about hedgehogs not being able to swim.
[src:sanic/sanic] The only exception is that he can swim in the Sonic the Hedgehog Adventure Gamebooks.
[src:sanic/sanic] When the seven Chaos Emeralds are collected and used, Sonic transforms into "Super Sonic" (スーパーソニック), a faster, stronger and invulnerable version of himself that can fly.
[src:sanic/sanic] In Super Sonic form, Sonic's irises turn red and his body becomes golden.
[src:sanic/sanic] As Sega's mascot and one of the key reasons for the company's success during the 16-bit era of video game consoles, Sonic is one of the most famous video game characters in the world.
[src:sanic/sanic] In 1993, Sonic became the first video game character to have a balloon in Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade.
[src:sanic/sanic] In 1996, Sonic was also the first video game character to be seen in a Rose Parade.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic was one of the three game characters inducted on the inaugural Walk of Game class in 2005, along with former rivals Mario and Link (both from Nintendo).
[src:sanic/sanic] One of a class of genes involved in fruit fly embryonic development, called hedgehog genes, has been named "sonic hedgehog" after him.
[src:sanic/sanic] On the other hand, Sonic's apparent romantic relationship with Princess Elise in the 2006 video game resulted in major criticism.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic's characterization and relationship with Eggman in *Sonic Boom* earned a positive response by Patrick Lee of *The A.V.
[src:sanic/sanic] Club* and Emily Ashby of *Common Sense Media*.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic has also been used as a symbol for Sega's various sponsorships.
[src:sanic/sanic] Between 1993 and 1997, Sega sponsored the JEF United Ichihara Chiba football team, during which period Sonic appeared in the team's uniform.
[src:sanic/sanic] During the 1993 Formula One championship, Sega sponsored the Williams Grand Prix team, which won the Constructors' Championship that year, as well as the team's lead driver, Alain Prost, winning the Drivers' Championship.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic was featured in the cars, helmets, and their rivals McLaren used to paint a squashed hedgehog after winning races over Williams.
[src:sanic/sanic] The 1993 European Grand Prix featured a Sonic balloon and Sonic billboards.
[src:sanic/sanic] Nintendo Power listed Sonic as their sixth favorite hero, stating that while he was originally Mario's nemesis, he seems at home on Nintendo platforms.
[src:sanic/sanic] They added that he has remained as one of gaming's greatest icons.
[src:sanic/sanic] In 2004, the character won a Golden Joystick Award for "The Sun Ultimate Gaming Hero".
[src:sanic/sanic] Later that year, Sonic was ranked as the most iconic video game character in an MSN rankings list.
[src:sanic/sanic] In 2011, *Empire* ranked him as the 14th greatest video game character.
[src:sanic/sanic] And he was voted 10th out of the top 50 video game characters of all time in *Guinness World Records* 2011 Gamers' Edition.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sonic ranked ninth on *GameDaily*'s Top 10 Smash Bros characters list.
[src:sanic/sanic] GameDaily also listed his "next-generation stumble" in their list of video game characters' worst moments, using his relationship with a human female as one of the worst parts of it.
[src:sanic/sanic] In 2024, a poll conducted by BAFTA with around 4,000 respondents named Sonic the Hedgehog as the fourth most iconic video-game character of all time, only behind Lara Croft, Mario and Agent 47.
[src:sanic/sanic] A Japanese team developing the Radio & Plasma Wave Investigation (RPWI) instrumentation for the *Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer* spacecraft, launched by ESA and Airbus in 2022, was able to gain Sega's approval to use Sonic as the mascot for the device.
[src:sanic/sanic] Specifically, Sonic appears on the logo of the RPWI in his classic design, the rendition being a redraw of how Sonic appears on the Japanese and PAL box art for *Sonic the Hedgehog*.
[src:sanic/sanic] An Internet meme called "Sanic" has been used based on a poorly drawn Sonic; typically, the meme uses one of Sonic's catchphrases but with poor grammar.
[src:sanic/sanic] Sega's official Sonic Twitter account has made numerous references to it, and it appeared in official downloadable content for *Sonic Forces* on in-game shirts.
[src:sanic/sanic] The meme also appears as a drawing in the theatrical film.
